5) One real life industry scenario where we can use above statistical concepts¶

In [313]:
#  Let's assume the case of an online clothing/apparels apllication like AJIO which is not that popular but give a decent discount rates 
# Considering the discount rates people tend to buy/order more products from this application. lets think there are 10 % of the products which are damaged and returned per week. If there are 100 orders
#  per week.

# We can use a Binomial Distribution concept to find the probability of how many products were returned back to the store or customers would have raised a return request.

# Let's find out the below probabilities
#  P(X = 0 returns)  - There were no returns and customers were satisfied with the products
#  P(X = 20 returns)   - There were exactly 20 returns
#  P(2 < X < 5 returns)  - There were greater than 2 returns but less than 5
In [314]:
p = 0.10 #(10 %)
n = 100 #sample size
#Using Binomial distribution to calculate probabilities
k = np.arange(0,101) # because considering  100 sample occurence also

#Using single sample Z - Test (Two Tailed test)
# population mean value for funds in million = 17.245
# population standard deviation for funds in million =  119.917
# population standard error = 11.9917
# Alpha = 5% or 0.05  Critical values for two tailed is + or - 1.96
#sample mean value for funds in million = 23.0838
SE = 119.917/ np.sqrt(n)
Z = (23.0838 - 17.245)/ SE
print(Z)

0.48690344154707
In [386]:
print(str(Z) + ' is within the critical values range + or - 1.96, then we FAIILED TO REJECT NULL- HYPOTHESIS')
